name: The Roast Beef of Old England
comments: The Richard Leveridge version duplicated much of Fielding’s version, replicating the first 2 ½ stanza’s, and then adding 5 more, performing to a more pleasing self-penned tune. Likely being published as "A Song in Praise of Old English Roast Beef" in print late in 1734 or early 1735. With the first performance by Leveridge at Covent Garden Theatre on 15 April 1735 : When mighty Roast Beef was the Englishman's food, It ennobled our veins and enriched our blood. Our soldiers were brave and our courtiers were good Oh! the Roast Beef of old England, And old English Roast Beef! But since we have learnt from all-conquering France To eat their ragouts as well as to dance, We're fed up with nothing, but vain complaisance Oh the Rost Beef, &c. The song became hugely popular, due to "a good tune with a rousing chorus", as well as catching the mood of the country with its satirical take of contemporary English eating French food rather than the "good old English roast beef". Over the ensuing 250 years the song has become a strongly patriotic & nationalistic song, being embedded in both the UK navy, as well as the USA marines and army.
adapted_from: When Mighty Roast Beef written by Henry Fielding

comments: Written during the 1930s Depression, as men struggled with unemployment and sought meagre dole payouts scattered across the Australian states, many resorted to illegal train travel. Police and railway authorities aimed to deter these free-travelling swagmen by intermittently inspecting trains, leading to arrests or forced removals in remote areas. Sergeant Small, stationed in Roma, ingeniously posed as a swagman on a goods train, coaxing hidden travelers into revealing themselves. The actual Sergeant Small, launched legal proceedings and successfully had the song banned. The record was withdrawn, and Morton recalled to the studio to record a new flip-side for The Martins and the Coys.

name: When Mighty Roast Beef
comments: Written by Scriblerus Secundus, a Henry Fielding nom de plume, for his ballad opera “The Grub-Street Opera” in 1931 as Air 39 and set to an earlier tune "The King's old Courtier", as "When Mighty Roast Beef": Air 39. (The King's old Courtier.) When mighty roast Beef was the Englishman’s food, It ennobled our Hearts, and enriched our Blood, Our Soldiers were brave, and our Courtiers were good. Oh! the roast Beef of England, And old England's roast Beef. But since we have learnt from all conquering France To eat their ragouts as well as to dance, Oh! What a fine figure we make in Romance! Oh! the roast beef of England, And old England's roast Beef! Lady. Servants are continually jealous of the least thrift of a Master or Mistress, they are never easy but when they observe Extravagance. However, it was not performed publicly until 1934 as part of Fielding’s parody “Don Quixote in England”, as Air 5. With the addition of "Old" before "England" in the refrain and the following stanza, "The Roast Beef of Old England”. Then, Britons, from all nice Dainties refrain, Which effeminate Italy, France and Spain; And mighty Rost Beef shall command on the Main. Oh the Rost Beef, &c. Oh the Rost Beef, &c.

name: The Loch Tay Boat Song
comments: The melody was collected in 1870 by Mrs. Cameron at Inverallort, from a traditional Gaelic Air. The form of the melody is that of a "iorram" having the function of giving the rhythm to rowers, a song to the oar. First appearing in the "Songs of the North" (1885 - 1926), it is believed that Sir Boulton translated the words from Gaelic into English. The original song is unknown. The song tells the tale of unrequited love, between a ferryman and the "nighean ruadh" girl, as the ferryman rows across Loch Tay towards Ben Lawers.
